1. Method with `@Transactional` annotation :

- **When you annotated a method with** `@Transactional`**, then, that method executes in a single database transaction.**

**For example :**

**If you have a code like this :**

    @Service
    public class UserDAOImpl implements UserDAO { 
        
        @PersistenceContext 
        private EntityManager em; 
     
        @Transactional   
        public void createUser(User user) { 
            em.persist(user);    
        }
    }

In this case, what happens is ? -  **JPA contains** `@PersistenceContext`**, which loads the** `EntityManager` **from the container.** **Then,** `@Transactional` **maintains the whole transaction by itself. You don&#39;t need to manually start and end the transaction.**

Now, if you use this `(propagation = Propagation.SUPPORTS)` with the `@Transactional`, then, what happens in this case is that **it sets the scope of the transaction to check whether there is any current transaction or not. If there isn&#39;t an current transaction, then the method will execute in a non-transactional way.** 

--------------------------------------------------------------

2. Method without `@Transactional` annotation :

- **In this case, you have to manage the transaction manually.**

**For example :** 

**If you have a code like this :**

     // add the persistence unit name  
     EntityManagerFactory emf = Persistence.createEntityManagerFactory(&quot;demo&quot;);
     EntityManager em = emf.createEntityManager();
     em.getTransaction().begin();
     User user = new User();
     user.setName(&quot;Michael&quot;);
     user.setAge(&quot;23&quot;);
     em.persist(user);
     em.getTransaction().commit();

**In this case, you have to get the bean manually. Then you have to start transaction and end the transaction as well. A lot more work to do in this.**

With `@Transactional(propagation = Propagation.SUPPORTS)`, **the transaction may be managed by the container** whereas without `@Transactional`, **the container will not manage the transaction at all**.

