You have a typo near the end of the long line, there is an extra `{}`  . Remove these and it should compile. 

IMO it would be better code style to have a function that returns such a rectangle, instead of packing that logic into the constructor. Example:

    class Rectangle
    {
        const double length;
        const double width;
    public:
        Rectangle(double length, double width): length(length), width(width) {}
        void outputRectangle(ostream&amp;) const;
    };

    Rectangle make_rectangle(const vector&lt;string&gt; &amp;internal)
    {
        double length = 0.0, width = 0.0;
        if ( internal.size() &gt; 2 )
            width = std::stod(internal[2]);
        if ( internal.size() &gt; 1 )
            length = std::stod(internal[1]);

        return { length, width };
    }

I would also suggest having `outputRectangle` be a free function, and have the member variables be non-`const`.  People can declare a `const Rectangle` if they want one and it makes life easier. 

For example your suggested function `Rectangle&amp; operator= (const Rectangle&amp;);` is actually impossible to implement while those members are `const`. Whereas with the non-const version, you don&#39;t need to write anything at all because the implicitly generated `operator=` will work.

    className(type1 arg1, type2 arg2):member1(arg1), member2(arg2) 
    {
        // constructor body
    }

This is called initializer list in c++. member1(arg1) and member2(arg2) are not functions.

The just initialize the data members with passed values. So you just need to remove those {} at end of initializer list and your code will work fine.

